# Adversary fixture: FM1-N3 — @keywords a. activates bare `a` as rdf:type shorthand
#
# Hypothesis: The `@keywords` directive in N3 introduces a shorthand mode where
# listed bare words become keywords. With `@keywords a.`, the bare token `a`
# in predicate position must be interpreted as rdf:type, identical to its
# meaning in Turtle. A parser that (a) ignores `@keywords` entirely, or
# (b) only accepts the `@keywords` form as a prefix-redefinition, or
# (c) treats bare `a` as a local name even after `@keywords a.`, will
# either reject the file or produce an incorrect predicate IRI.
#
# N3 spec (W3C Team Submission 2011-03-28) §3.1:
#   "@keywords" followed by a comma-separated list of bare names activates
#   those names as keywords. Once `a` is in the keywords list, `a` in
#   predicate position is syntactic sugar for `rdf:type`.
#
# Expected: parse succeeds; the two triples each use rdf:type as predicate.
# Divergence signal: AcceptRejectSplit, or ObjectMismatch where the predicate
# is treated as a local name rather than rdf:type.
#
# Spec: W3C N3 Team Submission §3.1 — @keywords directive.

@keywords a .

@prefix rdf: <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#> .
@prefix ex:  <http://example.org/> .

ex:Alice a ex:Person .
ex:Bob   a ex:Agent  .
